CLARKSDALE. Miss. = "Our
task in the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored
People is to focus Americas
attention on the plight of the
Negro unemployed in a more
dramatic fashion in 1864" said
Gloster B. Current, national
NAACP director of branches, in
an address at an Emancipation
Proclamation observance.


Demonstrations, marches on
City Halls, and demands on gov
errors for jobs by unemployed
Negroes, organized by the
NAACP, will be the order Of the
day this year. said Mr.. Current.


The NAACP will sponsor pro-
tests for jobs, Mr.. Current said,
because the rate Of Negro unem-
ployment is three times higher
than that for all Americans. In
Clarksdale alone, he observed,
six out Of every seven unem-
ployed persons are Negroes.

Current Speaks


At Emancipation


ProcIum alton Observance

Mayor Milt Graham has an
nounced the start Of a new pro-
gram designed to help keep citi-
zens better informed about mu-
nicipal operations and encourage
more active citizen interest and
participation in government.


Letters pf invitation are being
mailed to presidents Of % Phoe-
nix service clubs asking them to
invite their memberships. and
their families, to attend the Mon
day night informal meetings Of
the City Council as invited guests.

A different organization will be
contacted each week.


"This will be a continuing
program" said Graham, "and
when the first % clubs have Ns-
tied US, we will invite others. In
this way. citizens will be better
able to help us cope with the
problems Of today and the chal-
lenges Of tomorrow"


The first letter went to the Ex-
change Club Of Phoenix inviting
members to attend the February
II Informal Meeting Of the Coun-
Gil, starting at 1880 pm. b

MAYOR GRAHAM SETS FIRST


INFORMAL COUNCIL MEETING

You can expect lots Of exciting
new hobby kits to show up in the
stores this spring and summer.
More than 200 manufacturers
previewed their new ideas at the
9th annual trade show of the
Hobby Industry Association of
America, Inc, early in February.

Members Of the Purple Cross Nurses and First Aid Unit Of the
Canyon Temple 49, BPOEW auxiliary Friday, Feb
7 the Elks Lodge.


Officers include Mesdames Mary Thompson president Ruth
Curry PRESIDENT Ardeaa Wilson, Myrtle Jack
Cora Jackson and Lois Mitchell grand
organizer.


Other members Mines Lille Mae Hall, Bezora Holmes
Lacv tones. .
